                <div class="col-lg-5 col-sm-6">
                    <hr class="section-heading-spacer">
                    <div class="clearfix"></div>
                    <h2 class="section-heading">
                        How it works
                    </h2>
                    <p class="lead">There are three hierarchical levels in this technique: <strong>projects, tasks and actions</strong>.</p>
                    <p class="lead">Work is measured in indivisible <strong>25-minute</strong> units, which usually are followed by a subsequent 5-minute break.</p>
                    <p class="lead">Before starting to work, an <strong>active action</strong> must be selected. After the 25-minute period is finished, just <strong>confirm</strong> your work.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-lg-6 col-lg-offset-1 col-sm-6">
                    <img class="img-responsive" src="/Content/img/landing/work.png" alt="How it works">
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>
        <!-- /.container -->

    </div>
    <!-- /.content-section-a -->

    <div class="content-section-b">

        <div class="container">

            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-lg-5 col-lg-offset-1 col-sm-push-6  col-sm-6">
                    <hr class="section-heading-spacer">
                    <div class="clearfix"></div>
                    <h2 class="section-heading">
                        What you get
                    </h2>
                    <p class="lead">GTDoro stores the time spent working on different tasks for <strong>future reference</strong>. Just a few clicks are needed.</p>
                    <p class="lead">You'll get useful information to <strong>improve the organization and productivity of your projects.</strong></p>
                    <p class="lead"><strong>Tables, reports, calendars</strong> and <strong>charts</strong> show detailed information about your work.</p>
                    <p class="lead"><strong>Filter and sort</strong> your data in order to get exactly what you need.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-lg-5 col-sm-pull-6  col-sm-6">
                    <img class="img-responsive" src="/Content/img/landing/improvements.png" alt="What you get">
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>
        <!-- /.container -->

    </div>
    <!-- /.content-section-b -->

    <div class="content-section-a">

        <div class="container">

            <div class="row">
